</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,968]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,407,548,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Descriptive notes</emphasis>
. A description of this species was given by 
<bibRefCitation author="Tremouilles, E. R. &amp; Bachmann, A. O." box="[936,1323,548,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529" pagination="101 - 125" refId="ref7687" refString="Tremouilles, E. R. &amp; Bachmann, A. O. (1980) La tribu Cybisterini en la Argentina (Coleoptera, Dytiscidae). Revista de la Sociedad Entomologica Argentina, 39, 101 - 125." type="journal article" year="1980">Trémouilles &amp; Bachmann (1980)</bibRefCitation>
. Here we provide photos of the habitus (
<figureCitation box="[490,609,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,249,1676,1698]" captionTargetBox="[171,1414,205,1629]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[166,1421,193,1654]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1. Habitus in dorsal view of: A) M. ducalis, B) M. lherminieri, C) M. magnus; habitus in ventral view of: D) M. ducalis, E) M. lherminieri (Ecuador, Esmeraldas), F) M. magnus (Paraguay, Cerro Lambaré)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647352/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Figs 1C, F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[620,653,584,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,249,1959,1981]" captionTargetBox="[193,1409,484,1938]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[151,1436,481,1938]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus in lateral view of: A) M. ducalis, B) M. lherminieri, C) M. magnus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647354/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">2C</figureCitation>
) and focus on morphological characters of the male in different views (
<figureCitation box="[159,232,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="11.[151,249,1916,1938]" captionTargetBox="[213,1368,207,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[204,1372,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 8. Megadytes lherminieri, male, Ecuador, Esmeraldas: A) ventral view of head, left protarsus and left middle leg, B) dorsal view of left protarsus, C) ventro-lateral view of left hind leg; M. magnus, male, Paraguay, cerro Lambaré: D) ventral view of head, right protarsus and right middle leg, E) dorsal view of left protarsus, F) ventro-lateral view of left hind leg. Scale bars = 5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647366/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Figs 8</figureCitation>
D–F). The median lobe with both parameres of a specimen from Mariscal Estigarribia in 
<collectingCountry box="[1296,1401,621,645]" name="Paraguay" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
, is figured in ventral view (
<figureCitation box="[423,513,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,249,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Megadytes magnus: A) median lobe with parameres in ventral view, B) tip of median lobe in lateral view, C) median lobe in ventro-apical view to show the long nose-like tip. Scale bars = 1.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647362/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
), the tip of the median lobe in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[1004,1092,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,249,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Megadytes magnus: A) median lobe with parameres in ventral view, B) tip of median lobe in lateral view, C) median lobe in ventro-apical view to show the long nose-like tip. Scale bars = 1.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647362/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Fig. 6B</figureCitation>
), and the tip of median lobe in ventro-apical view (
<figureCitation box="[383,475,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,249,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Megadytes magnus: A) median lobe with parameres in ventral view, B) tip of median lobe in lateral view, C) median lobe in ventro-apical view to show the long nose-like tip. Scale bars = 1.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647362/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Fig. 6C</figureCitation>
). Note that 
<figureCitation box="[617,791,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="9.[151,249,1978,2000]" captionTargetBox="[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[199,1381,195,1953]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 6. Megadytes magnus: A) median lobe with parameres in ventral view, B) tip of median lobe in lateral view, C) median lobe in ventro-apical view to show the long nose-like tip. Scale bars = 1.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647362/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Figs 6A and C</figureCitation>
show the median lobe of the same individual, tilted at different angles.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="12" pageNumber="529" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,968]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,764,789]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Distribution</emphasis>
. Southern part of tropical and subtropical South America. The species was described from 
<collectingCountry box="[151,265,799,824]" name="Argentina" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[276,380,800,824]" name="Paraguay" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[435,534,800,824]" name="Uruguay" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
, and later recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[815,883,799,824]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Trémouilles 1989b) (
<figureCitation box="[1136,1218,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="16.[151,249,1904,1926]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1883]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1883]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 11. Distribution of the subgenus Bifurcitus in Central and South America: White line: distribution of M. lherminieri; black line: distribution of M. magnus; red spot: only known locality for M. ducalis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2647372/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1436,151,968]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,291,836,861]" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Habitat</emphasis>
. Unknown, probably similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Guerin-Meneville" baseAuthorityYear="1829" box="[656,820,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Megadytes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="529" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lherminieri">
<emphasis box="[656,820,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">M. lherminieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Most of the specimens in 
<collectingCountry box="[1131,1235,837,861]" name="Paraguay" pageId="12" pageNumber="529">Paraguay</collectingCountry>
were collected at light in a savannah region with temporary swamps and permanent farm dams. The swimming pool in Sao Paulo, were the single female has been collected, was not far away from a big reservoir or dam, overgrown with water lilies and water hyacinths (S. Gottwald pers. com.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
